a matter of privacy and are unaware of the law which protects the mother’s health. One out of 10 Nepali women believe low social status is reason enough to have an abortion. According to the Kathmandu Post, pregnancy is regarded as a woman’s "burden" that will mean the "end to all her hopes and dreams". Women consider abortion "is a termination of the life of an unborn baby, but it is a small price to pay to continue with her career or education". U K Shrestha, of the Public Health Science in the Kathmandu District Hospital, said women never feel any shame to seek an abortion. "They freely come to us and demand a safe abortion. I think it is the only good sign, a woman feels empowered to seek for oral contraceptives, an intrauterine device, or abortion when needed."

Nepal Mandela called for liberation

Nepal Mandela called for liberation

Liliesleaf, December 5, 2008

When Nelson Mandela holds up his fists above his head in a sign of triumph this week, perhaps he will think of Hsi Lekma or her children. Nelson Mandela published his best-selling book, Long Walk To Freedom, last week.
